  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several key statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report certain transactions\n- Helps detect and prevent money laundering\n\n2. Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Made money laundering a federal crime\n- Established criminal penalties for money laundering activities\n\n3. Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988\n- Expanded money laundering provisions\n- Focused on combating drug-related financial crimes\n\n4. Title III of the USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced money laundering prevention measures\n- Increased reporting requirements\n- Strengthened financial institution regulations\n\n5. Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Allows for asset forfeiture\n- Provides tools for investigating financial crimes\n\nAt the federal level, the primary agencies responsible for investigating and prosecuting money laundering include:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)\n\nAdditionally, many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws.",
